European inflation slipped in food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the sharp rise in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced the EU Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely - the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, together with rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene later on.
The inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, hit the record of twelve years; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation fell in the euro area as a result of rising food and energy prices.
Term wheat levies have increased by 88 per cent and soya levies have reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching nearly 100 dollars a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent today to 2.5 per cent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, yet the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by the beginning of December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its maximum level since 2002, while the Gallup never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the voters of the opposition - would mean more than two-thirds support (71 percent) compared to the support of a fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the limit necessary to have some parliamentary scandal: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the lowest point before - it has never been so high, 41% the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation particularly bad, while another 46% believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population has the deterioration of the situation and only one tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of those consulted, more than any previous Gallup survey, felt that the President of the Government was doing his job wrong than well.
13 percent of those consulted trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has 38 percent of those consulted.
54 per cent of the population does not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 per cent does not trust the President of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the dissatisfaction experienced vis-à-vis the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 per cent felt that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this ratio is currently only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believe that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the participation question answered that they would be sure to participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 per cent of the population would surely participate and another 15 per cent would probably believe their participation. On the basis of the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt of the result of the popular consultation.
Seventy-four percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of tuition fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service, and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of education rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has five times its prices
The average increase in price levels was maintained by 16 per cent in the hypermarkets of the Budaörs commercial gold triangle, with the difference that this year VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in Budaörs's trade triangle of gold the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper, but in all hypermarkets there was a much higher growth than the HUF thousand.
As prices in food supermarkets had already been "dispared" in December last year, so there was no drastic increase in percentage compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below the HUF 9 000, today they cannot do so for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 this basket cost HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the Central Bureau of Statistics data, although in Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a two-litre redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan's basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, regarding last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan by about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with that of this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during last Christmas prices felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of a product's circulation, he may lose an important profit in the margin that fits the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the basket of Napi reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while at the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price of now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, catastrophic growth in prices was recorded in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of essential consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the Central Bureau of Statistics figures: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent over the 12-month period.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst case only 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose a drastic price increase even on multinationals.
The hypermarkets do not complain in the commercial triangle of gold, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three shops visited no longer care about prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking preserved foods by pallets.
On the morning of Wednesday, in the three stores large queues were formed in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income falls short of their plans, not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene conditions in hospitals, overcrowded beds and overloaded staff do not favor infection control - says the head doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre department.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA infection and since then no major surgery has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, head doctor of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
This means that the number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded in hospitals, but no information is available.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are caused by MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once it is overly or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, become highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and rapidly spread under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicaemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic-resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff attends to them in rubber gloves and mask and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the diseases that carry MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come out in public light when MRSA infections are already occurring visible in the patient - said the head doctor of the epidemiologic center.
The European Union makes strict commitments to the application of antibiotics in human medicine and national directives are also in place to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, i.e., microbiological tests should be conducted to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by drip transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least for a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for the infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate prevention measures are being implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
Denying the blood alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been prepared on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of District XXII.
The possibility of driving drunk or in a stunned state can be excluded the then resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after the expert report on the case has been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary blood alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverages before getting behind the wheel.
The then chief of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle by doubling to Kossuth Lajos street of the XXII district, hit a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(This latter fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Transit Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when doubling.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police officer resigned and applied for his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of €400 million to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as energy.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungarian objective, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later when the credit agreement is extended.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the Innovation and Research Project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will again address the issue of whether or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the loan at the disposal of the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country mentioned earlier.
What, where and who buys on the EU's even cheaper market, which will be quickly increased?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred goal for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is certainly some Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slopes apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Costa del Sol", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also in the vicinity of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap area of Rus.
Similarly, the capital Sofia can be attractive, commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golfing paradises in Europe, so it can be an outstanding destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Precautionary investors are therefore already making their purchases, for example in the surroundings of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria also strive to change their life and way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but also come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in skiing paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to install here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in bad condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to then renew them.
They require good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
The second category is the buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included among the first 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group consists of real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital properties is growing steadily, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years they have experienced an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in the price of real estate considerably exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will be concluded on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Roadmap, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on this issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures for the time being, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, emissions of greenhouse gases will decline by 25 to 40 per cent until 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
There was also agreement on aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, under the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac es Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which the then 15 EU Member States pledged to meet 8 per cent of the decline.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - says the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
Much is at stake in Bali, since in two years' time the international agreement on climate policy will have to be signed in the long term, because otherwise, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emissions reduction system, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and would not prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the Earth's average temperature, which scientists believe would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: Special Units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "headquarters defence" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Community of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the real objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda hardly costs anything compared to conventional recruitment television spots - the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - on the other hand, inevitably they have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the carefully edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example on the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak as a maximum of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
