The party isn't always written with red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers in the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - that next year will be less - the working days will be reorganized.
Not even in the EU or North America are parties unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between a national holiday, a state holiday and a holiday.
The holiday days mainly relate to religious festivals and historical ephemerals.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter above all so that they can rest those who spent celebrating the old anus.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national festival on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on October 23, a day commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the foundation of the State, on May 1 the feast of work, on November 1 and 2 we remember our relatives and friends who died.
In addition, in our country are two-day feasts the Easter of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it often makes a bridge when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for extended weekends like this, on previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
He is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or after the feast.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and civil servants.
It is not mandatory, however, for companies and service institutions which, because of their role, work continuously even during public holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 the life in the country is practically stopped, since according to the experiences, most people "make bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our parties will coincide with midday or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First the agenda will be changed around the work party so that then, for four successive days, the workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26 will be working day, so that in return Friday, May 2 is a holiday.
The other change relates to the feast of October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, we will have to work instead of Friday 24.
On the other hand, the coming year during the year-end party will be able to rest, since from December 24th it will not be worked anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
