After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, the Westerners consider independence under the supervision of the European Union to be the only viable solution.
Pristina is prepared to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not resolve in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," announced the president of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" were held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, the former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, has expressed his regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to killings and deportations."
