After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not available to be consulted here only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced workers " , explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, if necessary, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents, " said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
