Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary process, which ended today with Congress's vote on amendments to the bill in the Senate, the Government has put to public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of having both of them come into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation in order to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activities of the entities for the efficient functioning of the markets.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves modernising financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new legislation will enable financial advisory services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (FIAs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are complemented by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment services companies to disclose on the market key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, in order to facilitate oversight by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Congressional Economics Commission, several amendments were incorporated, among which it is noted that the securitized debts are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given their high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated by what happened with the debt of high-risk US mortgages (subprime).
