Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like the Earth, something that had not been raised until now. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirls in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
Already for three decades researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays run from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, gave rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
It's not like that in Venus: if there was life there someday, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500°C, oscillating so that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possibly, Venus is a "diabolic" twin on Earth, but he's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, just for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers, emphasize not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds us of the wind flows in the upper terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost so large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equal to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like the Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had been agglomerated that remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
