Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the wooden boxes of red, blue and white, with the same sample that had cardboards of soap powder "Brillo".
According to Warhol, at the exhibition of his works in 1968 at the Museum Moderna Museet hundreds of Brick-cardboard boxes were exhibited. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the cardboard factory of "Brillo".
It was not works of art, but exemplars (which were only objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol made it possible to produce in Sweden a Shine-boxes of wood, but they were not exhibited at the Museum Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now speak of nearly fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost one hundred wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in fact, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
Warhol had been dead for three years now.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Museum Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First they were printed and crushed their tight silver and then painted them in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the painting was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed silver. Moreover, it is not about oil painting, but about acrylic painting.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from Andy Warhol's official Bright Boxing List," says Lars Nittve, director of the Museum Moderna Museet and adds that if the Authentication Commission "Andy Warhol Art" in New York will not come to any conclusion, the Museum Moderna Museet will classify these six boxes as the copies/objects of exhibition."
Already in July The Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious accusations" in which they are soap dust boxes.
But from that moment everything remained in absolute silence.
