Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blames the president, corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter that she could not answer for spilling blood.
Soldiers loyal to the government had raided the hotel using tear gas.
Almost two hundred soldiers had been squatting in the building for a few hours.
Almost half of them, including Trillanes, had a trial on Thursday for trying a coup d'état in 2003 that ended in a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, so he could suddenly deposit with about 30 sympathizers.
Obviously, the military police who were supposed to monitor him had passed into their ranks and followed their mutiny.
They entered the "Península" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood in the vicinity of the Noble Hotel.
The president called for an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the National Security Adviser, condemned the behaviour of the soldiers.
"People are sick of it," Trillanes said.
"We summon people to come to our ranks."
